mmunity support that propelled him to college and DREAM Act organizing but still landed in a factory job a few short years after graduation, and the early-exiters, like Gabriel, who failed to make meaningful connections in high school and started navigating dead-end jobs, immigration checkpoints, and a world narrowly circumscribed by legal limitations. This vivid ethnography explores why highly educated undocumented youth share similar work and life outcomes with their less-educated peers, despite the fact that higher education is touted as the path to integration and success in America. Mining the results of an extraordinary twelve-year study that followed 150 undocumented young adults in Los Angeles, Lives in Limbo exposes the failures of a system that integrates children into K-12 schools but ultimately denies them the rewards of their labor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChildren of illegal alienszUnited StatesxEducation. 0aChildren of illegal alienszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aChildren of noncitizensxEducationzUnited States. 0aChildren of noncitizenszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aIllegal immigrationzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aanthropologist.  abroken immigration system.  acollege student.  acollege-goer.  adaca.  adream act.  aeconomist.  afuture of an undocumented worker.  ak-12 schools.  alinguist.  amanual laborers.  amexican american immigrants.  amexican american youth.  asociologist.  atwelve-year study.  auncertain future.  aundocumented immigrants.  aunited states immigration policies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028726640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096241540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/